{"title_page": "Mdou Moctar", "text_new": "{{short description|Nigerien musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Mdou Moctar\n| image               = File:Mdou Moctar Milh\u00f5es de Festa 2014.jpg\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 =\n| caption             =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          = Mahamadou Moctar\n| native_name         =\n| native_name_lang    =\n| alias               = M.dou Mouktar\n| birth_date          = {{circa}}1986\n| birth_place         = Niger\n| origin              =\n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         =\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Blues rock]]\n| occupation          = musician\n| instrument          = guitar, vocals, synth\n| years_active        = 2008\u2013present\n| label               = [[Sahel Sounds]]\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             =\n}}\n'''Mahamadou Moctar'''<ref name=afropop>https://afropop.org/articles/mdou-moctar-talks-tuareg-film-and-music</ref>, known professionally as '''Mdou Moctar''' (also '''M.dou Mouktar'''; born {{circa}} 1986<ref>{{cite news|title=MUZIEK: Mdou Moctar \u2013 Toeareg-rockheld voor de jonge generatie|url=http://www.gonzocircus.com/muziek-mdou-moctar-toeareg-rockheld-voor-de-jonge-generatie/|accessdate=4 October 2014|work=Gonzo Circus|issue=123|date=4 September 2014}}</ref> or 1984<ref name=afropop />) is a [[Tuareg]] songwriter and musician based in [[Agadez]], [[Niger]], and is one of the first musicians to perform modern electronic adaptations of [[Berber music|Tuareg guitar music]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Anar|url=https://sahelsounds.bandcamp.com/album/anar|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|last=Kirkley|first=Christopher|title=Akounak: The feature film of a Tuareg guitarist in Agadez|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/454629120/akounak-the-feature-film-of-a-tuareg-guitarist-in?ref=card|work=kickstarter|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> He first became famous through a subtle trading network of cellphones and memory cards in West Africa.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|title=tahoultine, chopped and skyped|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2011/12/tahoultine-chopped-and-skyped/|publisher=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=24 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nMdou Moctar is a popular wedding performer and sings about Islam, education, love and peace in [[Tamasheq language|Tamasheq]].<ref name=wire>{{cite journal|last1=Allan|first1=Jennifer Lucy|title=Prince of the Desert|journal=[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]|date=October 2014|issue=368|pages=10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://associationtedhil.eklablog.com/mdou-moctar-musicien-touareg-du-niger-a32482660|title=Mdou Moctar, musicien touareg du Niger|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2012/08/mdou-moctar-desert-warrior/|title=Mdou Moctar, Desert Warrior|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> He plays a [[List of musicians who play left-handed#Guitarists|left-handed]] [[Fender Stratocaster]] guitar in a [[Tuareg people#Music|takamba]] and assouf style.<ref name=wire /><ref>{{cite web|title=Mdou Moctar/official|url=https://www.facebook.com/mdoumoctarofficial|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> He is originally from [[Abalak]] and has also lived in [[Tchintabaraden]] and [[Libya]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Audio: Mdou Moctar & Brainstorm 'Anar/Vanessa'|url=http://www.okayafrica.com/2012/08/13/mdou-moctar-brainstorm-anar-vanessa-sahel-sounds/|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Music from Saharan Cellphones|url=http://healthryder.blogspot.co.nz/2012/02/mdou-moctar-music-from-saharan.html|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MDOU MOCTAR\">{{cite web|title=MDOU MOCTAR|url=http://cafeoto.co.uk/mdou-moctar.shtm|work=Cafe Oto|accessdate=30 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330112337/http://cafeoto.co.uk/mdou-moctar.shtm|archive-date=30 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Albums==\nHis first album, ''Anar'', was recorded in [[Sokoto]], [[Nigeria]] in 2008 and prominently featured \"spaced-out\" [[auto-tune|autotuned]] vocals and the influence of [[Hausa music]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=wire /><ref name=\"MDOU MOCTAR\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Doran|first1=John|title=The playlist: the best Middle Eastern and North African music of 2014, with Noura Mint Seymali|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/dec/30/the-playlist-best-middle-eastern-north-african-music-of-2014|accessdate=25 January 2015|work=[[the Guardian]]|date=30 December 2014}}</ref> The album was not officially released at the time but the songs became hugely popular across the [[Sahel]] when they went viral through cell-phone music trading networks.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.okayafrica.com/2012/08/13/mdou-moctar-brainstorm-anar-vanessa-sahel-sounds/|title=Audio: Mdou Moctar & Brainstorm 'Anar/Vanessa'|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vanguardredmagazine.co.nz/mdou-moctar-anar-official-video/|title=Mdou Moctar \u2013 'Anar' (Official Video)|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> They reached a global audience when [[Sahel Sounds]] released his music on the ''Music from Saharan Cellphones: Volume 1'' compilation. Two songs were covered with English [[homophone]] lyrics by Brainstorm, an American band from [[Portland, Oregon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2012/03/of-love-and-eyebrows/|title=of love and eyebrows|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> ''Anar'' was released on vinyl in 2014 with a high price, due to \"predatory business practices\" from [[Sixt]] on Moctar's first European tour.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kirkley|first1=Chris|title=here be dragons|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2014/09/here_be_dragons/|website=Sahel Sounds|publisher=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis next album, ''Afelan'', was recorded live in Tchintabaraden and features \"rusty-edged jams and sun-weathered ballads\".<ref name=Weiss>{{cite web|last1=Holslin|first1=Peter|title=Master of Saharan Guitar: Mdou Moctar \"Anar\"|url=http://www.passionweiss.com/2015/01/22/mdou-moctar-anar/|website=Passion of the Weiss|accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> The title track is named after a celebrated historical/folkloric hero of the [[Azawagh#Population|Azawough]] of Western Niger.<ref>{{cite web|title=sahel vinyl|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2013/07/sahel_vinyl/|work=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref> It contains a cover of [[Amassakoul|\"Chet Boghassa\"]] by [[Tinariwen]].\n\nOn his first realizations and interest of an audience outside of the Saharan region, Moctar said in late 2014: \"\u201cI first met (Christopher Kirkley of Sahel Sounds) on the mobile phone as he had called me ... It was a weird conversation, as I thought my cousin was pulling a joke on me so I hung up. This American guy calling me, saying he wanted to work with me for my music, it just couldn\u2019t be real. He called me again and we talked. He came to visit me in my village and also sent me a lefthanded guitar, which is very hard to find in Niger. This guitar has crossed several African countries to arrive in my hands, I have been playing it ever since!\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Knik|url=http://occii.org/knik/interview-mdou-moctar/|work=\"An Interview with Mdou Moctar|accessdate=30 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nMdou Moctar released his fifth studio album ''Ilana (The Creator)'' in 2019, it was his first studio album recorded with a full band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/mdou-moctar-ilana-the-creator/|title=Mdou Moctar: Ilana (The Creator)|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> ''[[NPR]]''<nowiki/>'s Bob Boilen named the album \"perhaps the most fiery psych-rock of the 21st century\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/03/21/704818917/first-listen-mdou-moctar-ilana-the-creator|title=Mdou Moctar's 'Ilana' Is Perhaps The Most Fiery Psych-Rock Of The 21st Century|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> while ''[https://happymag.tv/ Happy Mag]'' placed it at no.13 on their list of \"The 25 best psychedelic rock albums of the 2010s\", labelling it \"serious music for a serious cause.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://happymag.tv/the-25-best-psychedelic-rock-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=The 25 best psychedelic rock albums of the 2010s|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> \n\n==Films==\nMoctar appeared in the short film ''I Sing the Desert Electric''.<ref>{{cite web|title=i sing the desert electric (download)|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2013/03/i-sing-the-desert-electric-download/|publisher=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=27 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe also has the starring role in the 2015 film ''Akounak Tedalat Taha Tazoughai'', which translates as \"Rain the Color of Blue with a Little Red In It\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mdou Moctar - Akounak Tedalat Taha Tazoughai TEASER|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9su1UxtaI7I|accessdate=27 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mdou Moctar protagoniza un nuevo filme documental: \"Rain the Color of Red with a Little Blue In It\"|url=http://www.conceptoradio.net/2013/12/27/mdou-moctar-protagoniza-un-nuevo-filme-documental-rain-color-red-little-blue/|work=conceptaradio|accessdate=30 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001154/http://www.conceptoradio.net/2013/12/27/mdou-moctar-protagoniza-un-nuevo-filme-documental-rain-color-red-little-blue/|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> It tells the story of a musician from Agadez, who struggles with competing artists, a difficult home life, romantic problems and his own internal strife; whilst riding around the [[Sahara|desert]] on a purple motorcycle.<ref>{{cite web|title=Artickle|url=http://www.conceptoradio.net/2013/11/13/sahel-sounds-algunos-artistas-africanos-nunca-han-visto-un-vinilo/|work=conceptoradio|accessdate=30 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001149/http://www.conceptoradio.net/2013/11/13/sahel-sounds-algunos-artistas-africanos-nunca-han-visto-un-vinilo/|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Singer |first=Matthew |title=Kickstart My Heart: Portland Blogger To Direct First-Ever Tuareg-Language Film in West Africa |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |location=Portland, Oregon |date=14 January 2014 |url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-31115-kickstart_my_heart_p.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201223807/http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-31115-kickstart_my_heart_p.html |archivedate=1 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film is an [[Homage (arts)|homage]] to [[Purple Rain (film)|''Purple Rain'']] and ''[[The Harder They Come]]''; and is influenced by ''[[Moi, un noir]]'', [[Jean Rouch]], [[Italian neorealism]] and [[poverty row]] films.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> It is the world's first [[feature film]] in a [[Tuareg languages|Tuareg language]], specifically a mixture of dialects from [[A\u00efr Mountains|A\u00efr]] and [[Azawagh]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mdou Moctar - Akonak (TEASER TRAILER 2)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VxEK2bjiwIU|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kirkley|first=Christopher|title=rain the color of blue with a little red in it|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2014/01/rain-the-color-of-blue-with-a-little-red-in-it/|work=sahel sounds|publisher=sahel sounds|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> The soundtrack features music performed on set and at [[L'Embobineuse]].<ref name=ost>{{cite web|last1=Kirkley|first1=Christopher|title=Akounak Tedalat Taha Tazoughai OST|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2015/06/akounak/|website=Sahel Sounds|publisher=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''Anar'' (2008)\n*''Afelan'' (2013)\n*''Akounak Tedalat Taha Tazoughai OST'' (2015)\n*''Sousoume Tamachek'' (2017)\n*''Ilana (The Creator)'' (2019)\n*''Ibitlan'' EP (2020)\n\n===Singles===\n*''Tahoultine'' (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/tahoultine-mw0002285863|title=Tahoultine|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n*''Anar / Vanessa'' (2012) (split with Brainstorm)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://7inches.blogspot.co.nz/2012/08/mdou-moctarbrainstorm-on-sahel-sounds.html|title=Mdou Moctar/Brainstorm on Sahel Sounds Records|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Compilation appearances===\n*''Music from Saharan Cellphones: Volume 1'' (2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewire.co.uk/news/19239/music-for-saharan-cellphones-vol.2-crowdfunding-lp-release|title=Music For Saharan Cellphones Vol.2 crowdfunding LP release|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> \n*''Music For Saharan Cellphones: The International Reworks'' (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boomarmnation.bandcamp.com/album/music-for-saharan-cellphones|title=Music For Saharan Cellphones |accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n*''The Mdou Moctar Covers'' (2012) (split with Brainstorm)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brainstormbrainstorm.bandcamp.com/album/the-mdou-moctar-covers|title=The Mdou Moctar Covers|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n*''Pop Music From Republique Du Niger'' (2012)\n*''Music from Saharan Cellphones: Volume 2'' (2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sahelsounds.bandcamp.com/album/music-from-saharan-cellphones-volume-2|title=Music from Saharan Cellphones: Volume 2|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n*''Ronald Paris / Mdou Moctar'' (2014) (split cassette with Porches)<ref>{{cite web|last=Cohen|first=Ian|title=Porches|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/16775-porches-leather/|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=22 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Porches./Mdou Moctar Split|url=http://seagreenrecords.bigcartel.com/product/porches-mdou-moctar-split|work=Seegreen Records|accessdate=30 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410223916/http://www.seagreenrecords.bigcartel.com/product/porches-mdou-moctar-split|archive-date=10 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''Rough Trade Shops Africa 13'' (2014)\n*''Mind The Gap #110'' (2014)\n*''Below The Radar 10'' (2014)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.facebook.com/mdoumoctarofficial Official Facebook page]\n* ''[http://sahelsounds.bandcamp.com/album/anar Anar]''\n* ''[http://sahelsounds.bandcamp.com/album/afelan Afelan]''\n* \"[http://vimeo.com/124081255 Akounak Teggdalit Taha Tazoughai]\"\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moctar, Mdou}}\n[[Category:Berber Muslims]]\n[[Category:Berber Nigeriens]]\n[[Category:Nigerien musicians]]\n[[Category:Tuareg people]]\n[[Category:Nigerien Muslims]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Berber musicians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Nigerien musician}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name                = Mdou Moctar\n| image               = File:Mdou Moctar Milh\u00f5es de Festa 2014.jpg\n| image_size          =\n| landscape           = <!-- yes, if wide image, otherwise leave blank -->\n| alt                 =\n| caption             =\n| background          = solo_singer\n| birth_name          =\n| native_name         =\n| native_name_lang    =\n| alias               = M.dou Mouktar\n| birth_date          = {{circa}}1986\n| birth_place         = Niger\n| origin              =\n| death_date          = <!-- {{death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date 1st) -->\n| death_place         =\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[Blues rock]]\n| occupation          = musician\n| instrument          = guitar, vocals, synth\n| years_active        = 2008\u2013present\n| label               = [[Sahel Sounds]]\n| associated_acts     =\n| website             =\n}}\n'''Mdou Moctar''' (also known as '''M.dou Mouktar'''; born {{circa}} 1986<ref>{{cite news|title=MUZIEK: Mdou Moctar \u2013 Toeareg-rockheld voor de jonge generatie|url=http://www.gonzocircus.com/muziek-mdou-moctar-toeareg-rockheld-voor-de-jonge-generatie/|accessdate=4 October 2014|work=Gonzo Circus|issue=123|date=4 September 2014}}</ref>) is a [[Tuareg]] songwriter and musician based in [[Agadez]], [[Niger]], and is one of the first musicians to perform modern electronic adaptations of [[Berber music|Tuareg guitar music]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Anar|url=https://sahelsounds.bandcamp.com/album/anar|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated2>{{cite web|last=Kirkley|first=Christopher|title=Akounak: The feature film of a Tuareg guitarist in Agadez|url=http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/454629120/akounak-the-feature-film-of-a-tuareg-guitarist-in?ref=card|work=kickstarter|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> He first became famous through a subtle trading network of cellphones and memory cards in West Africa.<ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web|title=tahoultine, chopped and skyped|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2011/12/tahoultine-chopped-and-skyped/|publisher=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=24 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nMdou Moctar is a popular wedding performer and sings about Islam, education, love and peace in [[Tamasheq language|Tamasheq]].<ref name=wire>{{cite journal|last1=Allan|first1=Jennifer Lucy|title=Prince of the Desert|journal=[[The Wire (magazine)|The Wire]]|date=October 2014|issue=368|pages=10}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://associationtedhil.eklablog.com/mdou-moctar-musicien-touareg-du-niger-a32482660|title=Mdou Moctar, musicien touareg du Niger|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2012/08/mdou-moctar-desert-warrior/|title=Mdou Moctar, Desert Warrior|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> He plays a [[List of musicians who play left-handed#Guitarists|left-handed]] [[Fender Stratocaster]] guitar in a [[Tuareg people#Music|takamba]] and assouf style.<ref name=wire /><ref>{{cite web|title=Mdou Moctar/official|url=https://www.facebook.com/mdoumoctarofficial|accessdate=12 October 2014}}</ref> He is originally from [[Abalak]] and has also lived in [[Tchintabaraden]] and [[Libya]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Audio: Mdou Moctar & Brainstorm 'Anar/Vanessa'|url=http://www.okayafrica.com/2012/08/13/mdou-moctar-brainstorm-anar-vanessa-sahel-sounds/|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Music from Saharan Cellphones|url=http://healthryder.blogspot.co.nz/2012/02/mdou-moctar-music-from-saharan.html|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"MDOU MOCTAR\">{{cite web|title=MDOU MOCTAR|url=http://cafeoto.co.uk/mdou-moctar.shtm|work=Cafe Oto|accessdate=30 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140330112337/http://cafeoto.co.uk/mdou-moctar.shtm|archive-date=30 March 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Albums==\nHis first album, ''Anar'', was recorded in [[Sokoto]], [[Nigeria]] in 2008 and prominently featured \"spaced-out\" [[auto-tune|autotuned]] vocals and the influence of [[Hausa music]].<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref name=wire /><ref name=\"MDOU MOCTAR\"/><ref>{{cite news|last1=Doran|first1=John|title=The playlist: the best Middle Eastern and North African music of 2014, with Noura Mint Seymali|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/dec/30/the-playlist-best-middle-eastern-north-african-music-of-2014|accessdate=25 January 2015|work=[[the Guardian]]|date=30 December 2014}}</ref> The album was not officially released at the time but the songs became hugely popular across the [[Sahel]] when they went viral through cell-phone music trading networks.<ref name=autogenerated1 /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.okayafrica.com/2012/08/13/mdou-moctar-brainstorm-anar-vanessa-sahel-sounds/|title=Audio: Mdou Moctar & Brainstorm 'Anar/Vanessa'|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://vanguardredmagazine.co.nz/mdou-moctar-anar-official-video/|title=Mdou Moctar \u2013 'Anar' (Official Video)|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> They reached a global audience when [[Sahel Sounds]] released his music on the ''Music from Saharan Cellphones: Volume 1'' compilation. Two songs were covered with English [[homophone]] lyrics by Brainstorm, an American band from [[Portland, Oregon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2012/03/of-love-and-eyebrows/|title=of love and eyebrows|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> ''Anar'' was released on vinyl in 2014 with a high price, due to \"predatory business practices\" from [[Sixt]] on Moctar's first European tour.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kirkley|first1=Chris|title=here be dragons|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2014/09/here_be_dragons/|website=Sahel Sounds|publisher=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=10 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nHis next album, ''Afelan'', was recorded live in Tchintabaraden and features \"rusty-edged jams and sun-weathered ballads\".<ref name=Weiss>{{cite web|last1=Holslin|first1=Peter|title=Master of Saharan Guitar: Mdou Moctar \"Anar\"|url=http://www.passionweiss.com/2015/01/22/mdou-moctar-anar/|website=Passion of the Weiss|accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> The title track is named after a celebrated historical/folkloric hero of the [[Azawagh#Population|Azawough]] of Western Niger.<ref>{{cite web|title=sahel vinyl|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2013/07/sahel_vinyl/|work=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref> It contains a cover of [[Amassakoul|\"Chet Boghassa\"]] by [[Tinariwen]].\n\nOn his first realizations and interest of an audience outside of the Saharan region, Moctar said in late 2014: \"\u201cI first met (Christopher Kirkley of Sahel Sounds) on the mobile phone as he had called me ... It was a weird conversation, as I thought my cousin was pulling a joke on me so I hung up. This American guy calling me, saying he wanted to work with me for my music, it just couldn\u2019t be real. He called me again and we talked. He came to visit me in my village and also sent me a lefthanded guitar, which is very hard to find in Niger. This guitar has crossed several African countries to arrive in my hands, I have been playing it ever since!\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Knik|url=http://occii.org/knik/interview-mdou-moctar/|work=\"An Interview with Mdou Moctar|accessdate=30 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nMdou Moctar released his fifth studio album ''Ilana (The Creator)'' in 2019, it was his first studio album recorded with a full band.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/mdou-moctar-ilana-the-creator/|title=Mdou Moctar: Ilana (The Creator)|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> ''[[NPR]]''<nowiki/>'s Bob Boilen named the album \"perhaps the most fiery psych-rock of the 21st century\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2019/03/21/704818917/first-listen-mdou-moctar-ilana-the-creator|title=Mdou Moctar's 'Ilana' Is Perhaps The Most Fiery Psych-Rock Of The 21st Century|website=NPR.org|language=en|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> while ''[https://happymag.tv/ Happy Mag]'' placed it at no.13 on their list of \"The 25 best psychedelic rock albums of the 2010s\", labelling it \"serious music for a serious cause.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://happymag.tv/the-25-best-psychedelic-rock-albums-of-the-2010s/|title=The 25 best psychedelic rock albums of the 2010s|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref> \n\n==Films==\nMoctar appeared in the short film ''I Sing the Desert Electric''.<ref>{{cite web|title=i sing the desert electric (download)|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2013/03/i-sing-the-desert-electric-download/|publisher=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=27 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nHe also has the starring role in the 2015 film ''Akounak Tedalat Taha Tazoughai'', which translates as \"Rain the Color of Blue with a Little Red In It\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Mdou Moctar - Akounak Tedalat Taha Tazoughai TEASER|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9su1UxtaI7I|accessdate=27 December 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Mdou Moctar protagoniza un nuevo filme documental: \"Rain the Color of Red with a Little Blue In It\"|url=http://www.conceptoradio.net/2013/12/27/mdou-moctar-protagoniza-un-nuevo-filme-documental-rain-color-red-little-blue/|work=conceptaradio|accessdate=30 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001154/http://www.conceptoradio.net/2013/12/27/mdou-moctar-protagoniza-un-nuevo-filme-documental-rain-color-red-little-blue/|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> It tells the story of a musician from Agadez, who struggles with competing artists, a difficult home life, romantic problems and his own internal strife; whilst riding around the [[Sahara|desert]] on a purple motorcycle.<ref>{{cite web|title=Artickle|url=http://www.conceptoradio.net/2013/11/13/sahel-sounds-algunos-artistas-africanos-nunca-han-visto-un-vinilo/|work=conceptoradio|accessdate=30 December 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131231001149/http://www.conceptoradio.net/2013/11/13/sahel-sounds-algunos-artistas-africanos-nunca-han-visto-un-vinilo/|archive-date=31 December 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Singer |first=Matthew |title=Kickstart My Heart: Portland Blogger To Direct First-Ever Tuareg-Language Film in West Africa |newspaper=[[Willamette Week]] |location=Portland, Oregon |date=14 January 2014 |url=http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-31115-kickstart_my_heart_p.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201223807/http://www.wweek.com/portland/blog-31115-kickstart_my_heart_p.html |archivedate=1 February 2014 |accessdate=27 February 2017 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The film is an [[Homage (arts)|homage]] to [[Purple Rain (film)|''Purple Rain'']] and ''[[The Harder They Come]]''; and is influenced by ''[[Moi, un noir]]'', [[Jean Rouch]], [[Italian neorealism]] and [[poverty row]] films.<ref name=autogenerated2 /> It is the world's first [[feature film]] in a [[Tuareg languages|Tuareg language]], specifically a mixture of dialects from [[A\u00efr Mountains|A\u00efr]] and [[Azawagh]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Mdou Moctar - Akonak (TEASER TRAILER 2)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VxEK2bjiwIU|accessdate=12 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Kirkley|first=Christopher|title=rain the color of blue with a little red in it|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2014/01/rain-the-color-of-blue-with-a-little-red-in-it/|work=sahel sounds|publisher=sahel sounds|accessdate=20 January 2014}}</ref> The soundtrack features music performed on set and at [[L'Embobineuse]].<ref name=ost>{{cite web|last1=Kirkley|first1=Christopher|title=Akounak Tedalat Taha Tazoughai OST|url=http://sahelsounds.com/2015/06/akounak/|website=Sahel Sounds|publisher=Sahel Sounds|accessdate=8 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Albums===\n*''Anar'' (2008)\n*''Afelan'' (2013)\n*''Akounak Tedalat Taha Tazoughai OST'' (2015)\n*''Sousoume Tamachek'' (2017)\n*''Ilana (The Creator)'' (2019)\n*''Ibitlan'' EP (2020)\n\n===Singles===\n*''Tahoultine'' (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/tahoultine-mw0002285863|title=Tahoultine|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n*''Anar / Vanessa'' (2012) (split with Brainstorm)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://7inches.blogspot.co.nz/2012/08/mdou-moctarbrainstorm-on-sahel-sounds.html|title=Mdou Moctar/Brainstorm on Sahel Sounds Records|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Compilation appearances===\n*''Music from Saharan Cellphones: Volume 1'' (2010)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thewire.co.uk/news/19239/music-for-saharan-cellphones-vol.2-crowdfunding-lp-release|title=Music For Saharan Cellphones Vol.2 crowdfunding LP release|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref> \n*''Music For Saharan Cellphones: The International Reworks'' (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://boomarmnation.bandcamp.com/album/music-for-saharan-cellphones|title=Music For Saharan Cellphones |accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n*''The Mdou Moctar Covers'' (2012) (split with Brainstorm)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://brainstormbrainstorm.bandcamp.com/album/the-mdou-moctar-covers|title=The Mdou Moctar Covers|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n*''Pop Music From Republique Du Niger'' (2012)\n*''Music from Saharan Cellphones: Volume 2'' (2013)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sahelsounds.bandcamp.com/album/music-from-saharan-cellphones-volume-2|title=Music from Saharan Cellphones: Volume 2|accessdate=15 June 2013}}</ref>\n*''Ronald Paris / Mdou Moctar'' (2014) (split cassette with Porches)<ref>{{cite web|last=Cohen|first=Ian|title=Porches|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/tracks/16775-porches-leather/|work=Pitchfork|accessdate=22 March 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Porches./Mdou Moctar Split|url=http://seagreenrecords.bigcartel.com/product/porches-mdou-moctar-split|work=Seegreen Records|accessdate=30 March 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140410223916/http://www.seagreenrecords.bigcartel.com/product/porches-mdou-moctar-split|archive-date=10 April 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''Rough Trade Shops Africa 13'' (2014)\n*''Mind The Gap #110'' (2014)\n*''Below The Radar 10'' (2014)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.facebook.com/mdoumoctarofficial Official Facebook page]\n* ''[http://sahelsounds.bandcamp.com/album/anar Anar]''\n* ''[http://sahelsounds.bandcamp.com/album/afelan Afelan]''\n* \"[http://vimeo.com/124081255 Akounak Teggdalit Taha Tazoughai]\"\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moctar, Mdou}}\n[[Category:Berber Muslims]]\n[[Category:Berber Nigeriens]]\n[[Category:Nigerien musicians]]\n[[Category:Tuareg people]]\n[[Category:Nigerien Muslims]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Berber musicians]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century singers]]\n", "name_user": "UltHumanSp", "label": "safe", "comment": "added full name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mdou_Moctar"}
{"title_page": "Bentleigh Greens SC", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname  = Bentleigh Greens \n| nickname  = The Greens <br> ''Pagkyprio'' (Pan-Cyprian)\n| short name = BGSC\n| coordinates       = {{coord|37|58|7|S|145|5|27|E|region:AU-VIC_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| ground    = [[Kingston Heath Soccer Complex]]\n| capacity  = 3,300<ref>{{cite web|title=Kingston Heath Soccer Complex|url=http://www.austadiums.com/stadiums/stadiums.php?id=409|publisher=Austadiums|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=KINGSTON HEATH SOCCER COMPLEX|url=https://int.soccerway.com/venues/australia/kingston-heath-soccer-complex/v2672/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n| season    = 2019\n|pattern_b1=_darkgreenhoops\n|pattern_b2=\n| leftarm1 = 008000\n| leftarm2 = FF6600\n| body1 = 008000\n| body2 = FF6600\n| rightarm1 = 008000\n| rightarm2 = FF6600\n| shorts1 = 008000\n| shorts2 = 000000\n|socks1=008000\n|socks2=000000\n| image     =\n| image_size = 170\n| fullname  = Bentleigh Greens Soccer Club\n| founded   = 1987\n| chairman  = Ray Georgiou\n| president = Con Bios\n| coach     = Nick Tolios\n| league    = [[National Premier Leagues Victoria|NPL Victoria]]\n| position  = 5th of 14\n| website   = http://www.bentleighgreens.com.au/\n}}\n\n'''Bentleigh Greens Soccer Club''' is an Australian semi professional [[Association football|soccer]] club based in [[Cheltenham, Victoria|Cheltenham]], a suburb of [[Melbourne, Victoria]]. The club was formed in 1986, by the [[Greek Cypriot]] community and currently competes in the [[National Premier Leagues Victoria]]. Bentleigh made nationwide headlines when it became the first club below the [[A-League]] to make the semi-final of the [[FFA Cup]] in [[2014 FFA Cup|2014]]. The Greens hit another milestone a year later when they claimed their first major trophy, the NPL Victoria title. In 2016, Bentleigh Greens became Victorian top-flight league premiers for the first time.\n\nBentleigh are one of six state league teams to have eliminated an A-League team in the FFA Cup, along with [[Heidelberg United FC]], [[Redlands United FC]], [[Green Gully SC]], [[Adelaide City FC]] and [[Blacktown City FC]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:LogoBentleighGreens.png|thumb|Former Bentleigh Greens logo]]\n\n===Formation and Early Years===\nIn 1986, a small group of former members of Cypriot Community's Soccer Club, Central City, met at 15\u201317 Heffernan Lane. This group determined to create a strong Greek Cypriot based team in Melbourne. There were two previous failed attempts, one in the mid-1950s and secondly Central City from 1977 to 1983 which ran under the control of the Cyprus Community of Melbourne and Victoria from 1977 to 1980.\n\nThe \"Founders\" at this initial meeting were Michael Christopher, Ray Georgiou, Andrew Nicolaou, Michael Iaonnou, Harry Theocharous, Phillip Philippou, Tony Antoniou and Harry Constantinou. After making a huge fund raising effort and gathering together 150 foundation members they were able to take over [[Diamond Valley United SC|Greensborough SC]] and move it to Victory Park in the City of Moorabbin. The name of the club was changed to Bentleigh Greens. The green colours were retained.\n\n===Rise to the Victorian Premier League===\nThe club competed in the First Division of the Provisional League in 1987 season. That year the club finished runners up to Chelsea on goal difference, achieving promotion to Victorian League Division 4. The club was promoted to Division 3 in 1989 after a second-place finish, after just two years in Division 4. Bentleigh amazingly were promoted to Division 2 in 1990, having just been promoted to Division 3 that year. Two more promotions followed in 1993 and 1995, taking the Greens from Division 2 to the [[Victorian Premier League]] for the first time in the club's history. The 1995 promotion was the fifth promotion for the club in nine years, marking a very impressive rise through the ranks of Victorian football for the recently established Bentleigh side.<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Clubs/B/BentleighGreensDH.html</ref>\n\nBentleigh went into their first ever VPL campaign under the management of Harry Chalkitis, managing a fourth-place finish and qualifying for the finals series. The Greens met [[Green Gully SC]] in the elimination final, but went down 3\u20131. The following campaign was even stronger for Bentleigh, finishing runners-up in the regular season, finishing just two points behind winners [[Altona Magic]], but then lost 4\u20131 to Green Gully in the qualifying final and 2\u20131 to Bulleen Inter Kings in the semi-final to crash out. [[Mark Bresciano]] scored the winner for Bulleen Inter that day.\n\nBentleigh were relegated in 2005, going down to the Victorian State League Division 1 for the first time since 1995. The side finished bottom of the league, managing just 16 points in 26 games. The Greens narrowly avoided successive relegations, finishing 10th in a 12 team league with the bottom two going down. The side finished just three points above the relegated [[Northcote City FC]]. Bentleigh were promoted back to the top flight in 2009, finishing second with 41 points. The side would have missed out on promotion and finished third had [[St Albans Saints]] not been deducted nine points that season.<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/2009SD1T.html</ref> In their first season back in the top flight, the Greens finished in 10th place, one above relegation.\n\nBentleigh made the VPL grand final in 2013, finishing third in the regular season. On their way to the final, Bentleigh beat [[Melbourne Knights FC]] 4\u20132 and then [[Northcote City]] 2\u20131, but lost to Northcote City in the grand final 3\u20132 in extra time.\n\n===2014\u20132015: FFA Cup Run and First Major Title===\nThe club made nationwide headlines after making it to the semi-final of the inaugural [[FFA Cup]] in 2014. The Greens beat [[Blacktown City FC|Blacktown City]] 1\u20130 in the Round of 32, [[Sydney Olympic FC|Sydney Olympic]] 2\u20131 in the Round of 16, [[Adelaide City FC|Adelaide City]] 2\u20131 in the quarter finals before going down 3\u20130 to [[A-League]] side [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]]. The match against Adelaide City was played in front of almost 2,000 people at [[Kingston Heath Soccer Complex]],<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/result-bentleigh-greens-2-1-adelaide-city/16uwcbtbx89p41jwntf1hf4ol6</ref> while the match against Perth Glory drew a reported 3,300 people.<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/matchcentre/Bentleigh-Greens-v-Perth-Glory/786063</ref> Bentleigh brought in a number of high-profile players for the 2015 season, including the likes of [[Daniel Visevic]], Steven Topalovic and Queensland trio Troy Ruthven, Matt Thurtell and [[Chris Lucas]]. The season hit a major snag when the Greens were knocked out of the [[2015 FFA Cup]] in the qualifying stages by the unfancied [[Ballarat Red Devils]] but ended in fine style with the Club winning its first ever major title when it beat [[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]] at Lakeside Stadium in the Grand Final, 3\u20131 after extra time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfootball.com.au/greens-defeat-south-in-grand-final-extra-time-extraordinaire/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913210451/http://www.mfootball.com.au/greens-defeat-south-in-grand-final-extra-time-extraordinaire/ |archive-date=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Bentleigh finished runners-up to South Melbourne in the regular season, missing out on the minor and major double on goal difference.\n\n===2016\u2013Present: More Silverware===\nThe Greens secured reigning NPL Victoria Gold Medal winner [[Kamal Ibrahim (footballer)|Kamal Ibrahim]],<ref>http://www.bentleighgreens.com.au/media/1243{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> but lost key first-team players Steven Topalovic, [[Daniel Visevic]] and [[Alastair Bray]],<ref>http://www.cornerflag.com.au/championship-trio-depart-greens/</ref> with Bray signing for [[A-League]] side [[Central Coast Mariners]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kounelis|first1=Jordan|title=Alastair Bray and Francesco Stella sign with Central Coast|url=http://www.mfootball.com.au/alastair-bray-and-francesco-stella-sign-with-central-coast/|website=MFootball|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> Bentleigh kicked off season 2016 by claiming the FFV Community Shield, beating [[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]] at [[Kingston Heath Soccer Complex|Kingston Heath]] 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kulas|first1=Damir|title=Bentleigh Bests South To Start 2016|url=http://www.footballfedvic.com.au/bentleigh-bests-south-to-start-2016/|website=Football Federation Victoria|accessdate=16 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307134827/http://www.footballfedvic.com.au/bentleigh-bests-south-to-start-2016/|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bentleigh again met rivals South Melbourne at the final qualifying stage for the [[2016 FFA Cup]]. The Greens would go on to smash their opponents 4\u20130, sending the side through to the national stage of the Cup competition.<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/ffa-cup-bentleigh-greens-ecstatic-after-thrashing-south-melbourne/1devirxl90gei1qicakej7hrfw</ref> In August, Bentleigh took out the [[2016 Dockerty Cup]], the second major trophy in its history and first [[Dockerty Cup]] title, with a 1\u20130 victory over [[Green Gully SC|Green Gully]] at [[ABD Stadium]] in [[Broadmeadows]], with Ryan Paczkowski scoring and Ryan Scott delivering an outstanding performance in goals.<ref>http://www.cornerflag.com.au/quintuple-alive-for-dockerty-cup-winners-bentleigh/</ref> Just four days later, the Greens picked up their third piece of silverware for 2016, winning the NPL Victoria minor premiership for the first time in its history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfootball.com.au/the-examination-bentleigh-claims-maiden-minor-premiership-in-style/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823103358/http://www.mfootball.com.au/the-examination-bentleigh-claims-maiden-minor-premiership-in-style/ |archive-date=23 August 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBentleigh were drawn against [[Adelaide]]-based side [[North Eastern MetroStars SC|North Eastern MetroStars]] in the Round of 32 of the FFA Cup in 2016,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfootball.com.au/victorian-teams-learn-ffa-cup-fate/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630175419/http://www.mfootball.com.au/victorian-teams-learn-ffa-cup-fate/ |archive-date=30 June 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> winning on penalties, with the game tied at 2\u20132 after 90 minutes and 3\u20133 after extra time.<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/matchcentre/MetroStars-SC-v-Bentleigh-Greens/862154</ref> Bentleigh were drawn away from home against [[Tasmania]]n side [[Devonport City FC|Devonport City]] in the Round of 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/westfield-ffa-cup-round-of-16-draw-revealed/mwukkjqvp7vb15n3iq6dnl1dg|title=Westfield FFA Cup Round of 16 draw revealed|work=Football Federation Australia|date=10 August 2016}}</ref> Battling torrential rain and a stubborn Strikers side, it took extra time for Bentleigh to win through to the quarter-finals, with Matthew Thurtell scoring the game's lone goal in front of 3,000 fans at Valley Road.<ref name=\"Round of 16 MD 2 wrap\">{{cite web|title=Westfield FFA Cup Round of 16 MD 2 wrap|url=http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/westfield-ffa-cup-round-of-16-match-day-2-wrap/1qiln19o3y0hm1trt2k61jbr1g|website=Westfield FFA Cup|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> In the quarter-finals, Bentleigh was paired with reigning Cup holders and [[A-League]] heavyweights [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]].<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/westfield-ffa-cup-quarter-final-draw-revealed/13a7fz8yu85821ucyewzhaxfob</ref> Two second half goals to the A-League side saw it win out 2\u20130 in front of 3,754 people at Kingston Heath, a record crowd for the venue.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lynch|first1=Michael|title=Soccer: Victory through to FFA Cup semi-final with 2\u20130 win over Bentleigh Greens|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/soccer/soccer-victory-through-to-ffa-cup-semifinal-with-20-win-over-bentleigh-greens-20160927-grpvd7.html|website=The Age|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref> After the clash, iconic captain Wayne Wallace announce his departure from the club after six years of service.<ref>{{cite web|title=FFA Cup swan-song as skipper Wallace departs for Hume|url=http://www.cornerflag.com.au/ffa-cup-swan-song-as-skipper-wallace-departs-for-hume/|website=The Corner Flag|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn preparation for the 2017 season, Bentleigh lost [[Kamal Ibrahim (footballer)|Kamal Ibrahim]] to [[Avondale FC]] and Liam McCormick to South Melbourne. However, the club exercised its muscle and added former A-League duo [[Ben Litfin]] and [[Andy Brennan]].<ref>http://www.cornerflag.com.au/litfin-lands-bentleigh-phoenix-stint/</ref><ref>http://www.cornerflag.com.au/former-knights-hoping-thrive-green/</ref> After a fourth-placed league finish, Bentleigh secured its second NPL Championship in three years when it beat Heidelberg United 2-1 after extra time in the Grand Final, with [[Lambros Honos|Ross Honos]] scoring in the 106th minute to win the tie.<ref name=\"2017 NPL Championship\">{{cite web|last1=Michell|first1=Tim|title=Goalkeeper Ryan Scott claims Jimmy Rooney Medal in Bentleigh Greens\u2019 NPL grand final win|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/south-east/sport/goalkeeper-ryan-scott-claims-jimmy-rooney-medal-in-bentleigh-greens-npl-grand-final-win/news-story/a63d211a9a93cae04673edda929252d4|website=Herald Sun|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> Goalkeeper Ryan Scott took out the Jim Rooney Medal, awarded to the best player on the pitch.<ref name=\"2017 NPL Championship\" />\n\nBentleigh became the 6th member federation side in [[FFA Cup]] history to knock out an [[A-League]] opponent when it beat [[Wellington Phoenix FC]] 1-0 at Kingston Heath in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-au/news/ffa-cup-wellington-phoenix-fall-to-npl-side-bentleigh-greens/1qt9li75fgf6j1xplthnrtj6rn|title=FFA Cup Wrap: Wellington Phoenix upset by NPL side Bentleigh Greens, Luke Brattan suffers serious injury {{!}} Goal.com|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref> Bentleigh beat [[Broadmeadow Magic FC|Broadmeadow Magic]] 4-0 at [[Wanderers Oval|Magic Park]] in the Round of 16<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/broadmeadow-magic-fc-v-bentleigh-greens-sc-ffa-cup-21-08-2018/1015426|title=Broadmeadow Magic FC vs Bentleigh Greens SC, FFA Cup, Round of 16, 21st Aug 2018|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref> and Heidelberg 1-0 in the quarter finals<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/bentleigh-greens-sc-v-heidelberg-united-fc-ffa-cup-26-09-2018/1020873|title=Bentleigh Greens SC vs Heidelberg United FC, FFA Cup, Quarter Finals, 26th Sep 2018|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref> to set up another clash with A League opposition, this time [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United.]] A goal in either half saw the Reds come away from Melbourne with a 2-0 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/bentleigh-greens-sc-v-adelaide-united-ffa-cup-05-10-2018/1028339|title=Bentleigh Greens SC vs Adelaide United, FFA Cup, Semi-Finals, 5th Oct 2018|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref> In the league, the Greens finished a point off top spot, but lost 4-3 to [[Avondale FC|Avondale]] in the semi-final.  \n\nIn January 2019, new A-League team [[Western United FC]] announced that Bentleigh head coach [[John Anastasiadis]] would join the club as an assistant coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/highly-rated-anastasiadis-lands-a-league-coaching-role-with-western-melbourne|title=Highly-rated Anastasiadis lands A-League coaching role with Western Melbourne|website=The World Game|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> Anastasiadis' last game in charge was an NPL Victoria Round 13 victory over the previously undefeated Avondale, propelling the Greens to second spot on the table.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/round_info.cgi?a=MATCH&fixture=70083787&c=1-10178-0-513758-0&pool=1|title=FFV - NPL Match Centre|website=SportsTG|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> John Gabrielson was appointed as the new head coach after Anastasiadis' departure. Gabrielson's tenure proved to be short-lived, with Frank McGrellis taking over in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://neoskosmos.com/en/142630/mcgrellis-answers-call-from-greens-to-coach-for-remainder-of-season/|title=Frank McGrellis answers call from Bentleigh Greens to coach remainder of season {{!}} Neos Kosmos|last=Stogiannou|first=George|date=2019-08-01|website=English Edition|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> After [[Kingston City FC|Kingston City]]'s relegation from the NPL Victoria was confirmed, Kingston's coach Nick Tolios was confirmed as the new Bentleigh Greens coach, mid-way through the 2019 NPL Victoria finals series. Tolios led the Greens to a 2-1 victory over premiers Heidelberg and a penalty shoot-out win over Avondale in the NPL Victoria Grand Final at [[AAMI Park]] to make it three championships in five years for the Cheltenham-based club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyfootballshow.com/greens-make-it-three-championships-in-five-years-with-shootout-win-over-avondale/,%20https://dailyfootballshow.com/?amp=1|title=Greens make it three championships in five years with shootout win over Avondale. {{!}} Daily Football Show|last=Lynch|first=Joey|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\n==Current squad==\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=1|nat=AUS|name=Ryan Scott|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=4|nat=AUS|name=Charlie Fry|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=5|nat=AUS|name=Jack Webster|pos=DF}} ''([[captain (association football)|captain]])'' \n{{Fs player|other=|no=6|nat=AUS|name=Troy Ruthven|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=7|nat=AUS|name=[[Kieran Dover]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=8|nat=AUS|name=[[Broadie Taylor]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=9|nat=AUS|name=[[Ben Litfin]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=10|nat=AUS|name=Tyson Holmes|pos=MF}} ''([[vice-captain|third captain]])''\n{{Fs player|other=|no=34|nat=Greece|name=Marios Gerondaras|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=14|nat=AUS|name=Marco Jankovi\u0107|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=15|nat=AUS|name=[[Ross Archibald]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=32|nat=AUS|name=Evan Fabiatos|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=18|nat=AUS|name=Matt Thurtell|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=19|nat=Germany|name=Arnold Sewell|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=20|nat=AUS|name=Michael Stark|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=23|nat=AUS|name=Trent Clulow|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=25|nat=AUS|name=Keanu Moore|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=38|nat=Japan|name=Futa Nakumura|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=30|nat=AUS|name=Joe O'Connor|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|other=|no=42|nat=AUS|name=Damion Wilson|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|other=Transferred to Western United FC|no=|nat=AUS|name=Valentino Yuel|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bentleighgreens.com.au/|title=Home 2019|website=Bentleigh Green Soccer Club|language=en-AU|access-date=2020-04-22}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[National Premier Leagues Victoria]]''' Champions 2015, 2017, 2019\n*'''[[National Premier Leagues Victoria]]''' Premiers 2016\n*'''[[Victorian Premier League]]''' Finalists 1996, 1997, 2001, 2002, 2019\n*'''[[Victorian State League Division 1]]''' Champions 1995\n*'''[[Victorian State League Division 2]]''' Runners Up 1993\n*'''[[Victorian State League Division 3]]''' Runners Up 1990\n*'''[[Victorian State League Division 4]]''' Runners Up 1989\n*'''[[Dockerty Cup]]''' Champions 2016, 2018\n*'''[[Dockerty Cup]]''' Runners Up 2017\n\n*'''[[FFV Community Shield]]''' Champions 2016, 2017, 2019\n*'''Hellenic Cup''' Champions 1991, 1996, 1997, 2002, 2003\n\n==Individual honours==\n*'''Victorian Premier League Player of the Year Award'''\n1996&nbsp;\u2013 Ike Alagiozidis\n\n2002&nbsp;\u2013 Jim Kourtis\n\n*'''Bill Fleming Medal'''\n1996&nbsp;\u2013 Ike Alagiozidis\n\n*'''Victorian Premier League Coach of the Year Award'''\n1997&nbsp;\u2013 Harry Chalkitis\n\n*'''Victorian Premier League Leading Goalscorer Award'''\n2002&nbsp;\u2013 Juan Nilo\n\n*'''Victorian Premier League Goalkeeper of the Year Award'''\n2002&nbsp;\u2013 Jim Kourtis\n\n*'''Victorian Premier League Under 21 Player of the Year Award'''\n1996&nbsp;\u2013 Vlad Babic\n\n==Competition timeline==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size:85%;width:99%; text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=2 width=5%|Season\n! colspan=11|League\n! rowspan=2 width=9%|NPL Playoffs\n! colspan=3|Cup\n|-\n! width=5%|Division\n! width=3%|{{Tooltip|Pld|Played}}\n! width=3%|{{Tooltip|W|Games won}}\n! width=3%|{{Tooltip|D|Games drawn}}\n! width=3%|{{Tooltip|L|Games lost}}\n! width=3%|{{Tooltip|GF|Goals scored}}\n! width=3%|{{Tooltip|GA|Goals against}}\n! width=3%|{{Tooltip|+/-|Goals difference}}\n! width=3%|{{Tooltip|Pts|Points}}\n! width=5%|Position\n! width=9%|Finals\n! width=9%|FFA Cup\n! width=9%|FFV Dockerty Cup\n! width=9%|FFV Community Shield\n|-\n|[[2014 National Premier Leagues|'''2014''']]\n|[[National Premier Leagues|NPL V]]\n|26\n|12\n|7\n|7\n|48\n|35\n|13\n|'''43'''\n|[[2014 Football Federation Victoria season|4th]]\n|Not contested\n|DNQ\n|Semi Finalist\n|Semi Finalist\n|Not contested\n|-\n|[[2015 National Premier Leagues|'''2015''']]\n|[[National Premier Leagues|NPL V]]\n|26\n|17\n|7\n|2\n|48\n|25\n|23\n|'''58'''\n|bgcolor=silver|[[2015 Football Federation Victoria season|2nd]]\n|bgcolor=gold|Champion\n|DNQ\n|Round 5\n|5th Round\n|DNQ\n|-\n|[[2016 National Premier Leagues|'''2016''']]\n|[[National Premier Leagues|NPL V]]\n|26\n|18\n|5\n|3\n|61\n|22\n|39\n|'''59'''\n|bgcolor=gold|[[2015 Football Federation Victoria season|1st]]\n|Semi Finalist\n|Quarter Finalist\n|Quarter Finalist\n|bgcolor=gold|Winner\n|bgcolor=gold|Winner\n|-\n|[[2017 National Premier Leagues|'''2017''']]\n|[[National Premier Leagues|NPL V]]\n|26\n|13\n|7\n|6\n|44\n|30\n|14\n|'''46'''\n|4th\n|bgcolor=gold|Champion\n|DNQ\n|Round of 16\n|bgcolor=silver|Runner-Up\n|bgcolor=gold|Winner\n|-\n|[[2018 National Premier Leagues|'''2018''']]\n|[[National Premier Leagues|NPL V]]\n|26\n|18\n|4\n|4\n|53\n|28\n|25\n|'''58'''\n|bgcolor=silver|2nd\n|Semi Finalist\n|DNQ\n|Round 7\n|bgcolor=gold|Winner\n|bgcolor=silver|Runner-Up\n|-\n|[[2019 National Premier Leagues|'''2019''']]\n|[[National Premier Leagues Victoria|NPL V]]\n|26\n|13\n|4\n|9\n|47\n|45\n|2\n|43\n|5th\n|bgcolor=gold|Champion\n|DNQ\n|Round 6\n|DNQ\n|bgcolor=gold|Winner\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.bentleighgreens.com.au/ Official club website]\n* [http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Clubs/B/BentleighGreensDH.html Bentleigh Greens on OzFootball]\n\n{{Soccer in Australia}}\n{{Football Federation Victoria}}\n{{Victorian Premier League seasons|state=collapsed}}\n{{National Premier Leagues Victoria stadiums|state=collapsed}}\n\n\n[[Category:National Premier Leagues clubs]]\n[[Category:Soccer clubs in Victoria (Australia)]]\n[[Category:Victorian Premier League teams]]\n[[Category:Greek-Australian culture in Victoria]]\n[[Category:Association football clubs established in 1986]]\n[[Category:1986 establishments in Australia]]\n[[Category:Bentleigh Greens SC]]\n[[Category:Diaspora sports clubs in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}}\n{{Infobox football club\n| clubname  = Bentleigh Greens \n| nickname  = The Greens <br> ''Pagkyprio'' (Pan-Cyprian)\n| short name = BGSC\n| coordinates       = {{coord|37|58|7|S|145|5|27|E|region:AU-VIC_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| ground    = [[Kingston Heath Soccer Complex]]\n| capacity  = 3,300<ref>{{cite web|title=Kingston Heath Soccer Complex|url=http://www.austadiums.com/stadiums/stadiums.php?id=409|publisher=Austadiums|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=KINGSTON HEATH SOCCER COMPLEX|url=https://int.soccerway.com/venues/australia/kingston-heath-soccer-complex/v2672/|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=17 February 2016}}</ref>\n| season    = 2019\n|pattern_b1=_darkgreenhoops\n|pattern_b2=\n| leftarm1 = 008000\n| leftarm2 = FF6600\n| body1 = 008000\n| body2 = FF6600\n| rightarm1 = 008000\n| rightarm2 = FF6600\n| shorts1 = 008000\n| shorts2 = 000000\n|socks1=008000\n|socks2=000000\n| image     =\n| image_size = 170\n| fullname  = Bentleigh Greens Soccer Club\n| founded   = 1987\n| chairman  = Ray Georgiou\n| president = Con Bios\n| coach     = Nick Tolios\n| league    = [[National Premier Leagues Victoria|NPL Victoria]]\n| position  = 5th of 14\n| website   = http://www.bentleighgreens.com.au/\n}}\n\n'''Bentleigh Greens Soccer Club''' is an Australian semi professional [[Association football|soccer]] club based in [[Cheltenham, Victoria|Cheltenham]], a suburb of [[Melbourne, Victoria]]. The club was formed in 1986, by the [[Greek Cypriot]] community and currently competes in the [[National Premier Leagues Victoria]]. Bentleigh made nationwide headlines when it became the first club below the [[A-League]] to make the semi-final of the [[FFA Cup]] in [[2014 FFA Cup|2014]]. The Greens hit another milestone a year later when they claimed their first major trophy, the NPL Victoria title. In 2016, Bentleigh Greens became Victorian top-flight league premiers for the first time.\n\nBentleigh are one of six state league teams to have eliminated an A-League team in the FFA Cup, along with [[Heidelberg United FC]], [[Redlands United FC]], [[Green Gully SC]], [[Adelaide City FC]] and [[Blacktown City FC]].\n\n==History==\n[[File:LogoBentleighGreens.png|thumb|Former Bentleigh Greens logo]]\n\n===Formation and Early Years===\nIn 1986, a small group of former members of Cypriot Community's Soccer Club, Central City, met at 15\u201317 Heffernan Lane. This group determined to create a strong Greek Cypriot based team in Melbourne. There were two previous failed attempts, one in the mid-1950s and secondly Central City from 1977 to 1983 which ran under the control of the Cyprus Community of Melbourne and Victoria from 1977 to 1980.\n\nThe \"Founders\" at this initial meeting were Michael Christopher, Ray Georgiou, Andrew Nicolaou, Michael Iaonnou, Harry Theocharous, Phillip Philippou, Tony Antoniou and Harry Constantinou. After making a huge fund raising effort and gathering together 150 foundation members they were able to take over [[Diamond Valley United SC|Greensborough SC]] and move it to Victory Park in the City of Moorabbin. The name of the club was changed to Bentleigh Greens. The green colours were retained.\n\n===Rise to the Victorian Premier League===\nThe club competed in the First Division of the Provisional League in 1987 season. That year the club finished runners up to Chelsea on goal difference, achieving promotion to Victorian League Division 4. The club was promoted to Division 3 in 1989 after a second-place finish, after just two years in Division 4. Bentleigh amazingly were promoted to Division 2 in 1990, having just been promoted to Division 3 that year. Two more promotions followed in 1993 and 1995, taking the Greens from Division 2 to the [[Victorian Premier League]] for the first time in the club's history. The 1995 promotion was the fifth promotion for the club in nine years, marking a very impressive rise through the ranks of Victorian football for the recently established Bentleigh side.<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/Clubs/B/BentleighGreensDH.html</ref>\n\nBentleigh went into their first ever VPL campaign under the management of Harry Chalkitis, managing a fourth-place finish and qualifying for the finals series. The Greens met [[Green Gully SC]] in the elimination final, but went down 3\u20131. The following campaign was even stronger for Bentleigh, finishing runners-up in the regular season, finishing just two points behind winners [[Altona Magic]], but then lost 4\u20131 to Green Gully in the qualifying final and 2\u20131 to Bulleen Inter Kings in the semi-final to crash out. [[Mark Bresciano]] scored the winner for Bulleen Inter that day.\n\nBentleigh were relegated in 2005, going down to the Victorian State League Division 1 for the first time since 1995. The side finished bottom of the league, managing just 16 points in 26 games. The Greens narrowly avoided successive relegations, finishing 10th in a 12 team league with the bottom two going down. The side finished just three points above the relegated [[Northcote City FC]]. Bentleigh were promoted back to the top flight in 2009, finishing second with 41 points. The side would have missed out on promotion and finished third had [[St Albans Saints]] not been deducted nine points that season.<ref>http://www.ozfootball.net/ark/States/VIC/2009SD1T.html</ref> In their first season back in the top flight, the Greens finished in 10th place, one above relegation.\n\nBentleigh made the VPL grand final in 2013, finishing third in the regular season. On their way to the final, Bentleigh beat [[Melbourne Knights FC]] 4\u20132 and then [[Northcote City]] 2\u20131, but lost to Northcote City in the grand final 3\u20132 in extra time.\n\n===2014\u20132015: FFA Cup Run and First Major Title===\nThe club made nationwide headlines after making it to the semi-final of the inaugural [[FFA Cup]] in 2014. The Greens beat [[Blacktown City FC|Blacktown City]] 1\u20130 in the Round of 32, [[Sydney Olympic FC|Sydney Olympic]] 2\u20131 in the Round of 16, [[Adelaide City FC|Adelaide City]] 2\u20131 in the quarter finals before going down 3\u20130 to [[A-League]] side [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]]. The match against Adelaide City was played in front of almost 2,000 people at [[Kingston Heath Soccer Complex]],<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/result-bentleigh-greens-2-1-adelaide-city/16uwcbtbx89p41jwntf1hf4ol6</ref> while the match against Perth Glory drew a reported 3,300 people.<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/matchcentre/Bentleigh-Greens-v-Perth-Glory/786063</ref> Bentleigh brought in a number of high-profile players for the 2015 season, including the likes of [[Daniel Visevic]], Steven Topalovic and Queensland trio Troy Ruthven, Matt Thurtell and [[Chris Lucas]]. The season hit a major snag when the Greens were knocked out of the [[2015 FFA Cup]] in the qualifying stages by the unfancied [[Ballarat Red Devils]] but ended in fine style with the Club winning its first ever major title when it beat [[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]] at Lakeside Stadium in the Grand Final, 3\u20131 after extra time.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfootball.com.au/greens-defeat-south-in-grand-final-extra-time-extraordinaire/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150913210451/http://www.mfootball.com.au/greens-defeat-south-in-grand-final-extra-time-extraordinaire/ |archive-date=13 September 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Bentleigh finished runners-up to South Melbourne in the regular season, missing out on the minor and major double on goal difference.\n\n===2016\u2013Present: More Silverware===\nThe Greens secured reigning NPL Victoria Gold Medal winner [[Kamal Ibrahim (footballer)|Kamal Ibrahim]],<ref>http://www.bentleighgreens.com.au/media/1243{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> but lost key first-team players Steven Topalovic, [[Daniel Visevic]] and [[Alastair Bray]],<ref>http://www.cornerflag.com.au/championship-trio-depart-greens/</ref> with Bray signing for [[A-League]] side [[Central Coast Mariners]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kounelis|first1=Jordan|title=Alastair Bray and Francesco Stella sign with Central Coast|url=http://www.mfootball.com.au/alastair-bray-and-francesco-stella-sign-with-central-coast/|website=MFootball|accessdate=4 January 2016}}</ref> Bentleigh kicked off season 2016 by claiming the FFV Community Shield, beating [[South Melbourne FC|South Melbourne]] at [[Kingston Heath Soccer Complex|Kingston Heath]] 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kulas|first1=Damir|title=Bentleigh Bests South To Start 2016|url=http://www.footballfedvic.com.au/bentleigh-bests-south-to-start-2016/|website=Football Federation Victoria|accessdate=16 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307134827/http://www.footballfedvic.com.au/bentleigh-bests-south-to-start-2016/|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Bentleigh again met rivals South Melbourne at the final qualifying stage for the [[2016 FFA Cup]]. The Greens would go on to smash their opponents 4\u20130, sending the side through to the national stage of the Cup competition.<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/ffa-cup-bentleigh-greens-ecstatic-after-thrashing-south-melbourne/1devirxl90gei1qicakej7hrfw</ref> In August, Bentleigh took out the [[2016 Dockerty Cup]], the second major trophy in its history and first [[Dockerty Cup]] title, with a 1\u20130 victory over [[Green Gully SC|Green Gully]] at [[ABD Stadium]] in [[Broadmeadows]], with Ryan Paczkowski scoring and Ryan Scott delivering an outstanding performance in goals.<ref>http://www.cornerflag.com.au/quintuple-alive-for-dockerty-cup-winners-bentleigh/</ref> Just four days later, the Greens picked up their third piece of silverware for 2016, winning the NPL Victoria minor premiership for the first time in its history.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfootball.com.au/the-examination-bentleigh-claims-maiden-minor-premiership-in-style/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=23 August 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160823103358/http://www.mfootball.com.au/the-examination-bentleigh-claims-maiden-minor-premiership-in-style/ |archive-date=23 August 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nBentleigh were drawn against [[Adelaide]]-based side [[North Eastern MetroStars SC|North Eastern MetroStars]] in the Round of 32 of the FFA Cup in 2016,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mfootball.com.au/victorian-teams-learn-ffa-cup-fate/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=1 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160630175419/http://www.mfootball.com.au/victorian-teams-learn-ffa-cup-fate/ |archive-date=30 June 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> winning on penalties, with the game tied at 2\u20132 after 90 minutes and 3\u20133 after extra time.<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/matchcentre/MetroStars-SC-v-Bentleigh-Greens/862154</ref> Bentleigh were drawn away from home against [[Tasmania]]n side [[Devonport City FC|Devonport City]] in the Round of 16.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/westfield-ffa-cup-round-of-16-draw-revealed/mwukkjqvp7vb15n3iq6dnl1dg|title=Westfield FFA Cup Round of 16 draw revealed|work=Football Federation Australia|date=10 August 2016}}</ref> Battling torrential rain and a stubborn Strikers side, it took extra time for Bentleigh to win through to the quarter-finals, with Matthew Thurtell scoring the game's lone goal in front of 3,000 fans at Valley Road.<ref name=\"Round of 16 MD 2 wrap\">{{cite web|title=Westfield FFA Cup Round of 16 MD 2 wrap|url=http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/westfield-ffa-cup-round-of-16-match-day-2-wrap/1qiln19o3y0hm1trt2k61jbr1g|website=Westfield FFA Cup|accessdate=30 August 2016}}</ref> In the quarter-finals, Bentleigh was paired with reigning Cup holders and [[A-League]] heavyweights [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]].<ref>http://www.theffacup.com.au/article/westfield-ffa-cup-quarter-final-draw-revealed/13a7fz8yu85821ucyewzhaxfob</ref> Two second half goals to the A-League side saw it win out 2\u20130 in front of 3,754 people at Kingston Heath, a record crowd for the venue.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lynch|first1=Michael|title=Soccer: Victory through to FFA Cup semi-final with 2\u20130 win over Bentleigh Greens|url=http://www.theage.com.au/sport/soccer/soccer-victory-through-to-ffa-cup-semifinal-with-20-win-over-bentleigh-greens-20160927-grpvd7.html|website=The Age|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref> After the clash, iconic captain Wayne Wallace announce his departure from the club after six years of service.<ref>{{cite web|title=FFA Cup swan-song as skipper Wallace departs for Hume|url=http://www.cornerflag.com.au/ffa-cup-swan-song-as-skipper-wallace-departs-for-hume/|website=The Corner Flag|accessdate=28 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn preparation for the 2017 season, Bentleigh lost [[Kamal Ibrahim (footballer)|Kamal Ibrahim]] to [[Avondale FC]] and Liam McCormick to South Melbourne. However, the club exercised its muscle and added former A-League duo [[Ben Litfin]] and [[Andy Brennan]].<ref>http://www.cornerflag.com.au/litfin-lands-bentleigh-phoenix-stint/</ref><ref>http://www.cornerflag.com.au/former-knights-hoping-thrive-green/</ref> After a fourth-placed league finish, Bentleigh secured its second NPL Championship in three years when it beat Heidelberg United 2-1 after extra time in the Grand Final, with [[Lambros Honos|Ross Honos]] scoring in the 106th minute to win the tie.<ref name=\"2017 NPL Championship\">{{cite web|last1=Michell|first1=Tim|title=Goalkeeper Ryan Scott claims Jimmy Rooney Medal in Bentleigh Greens\u2019 NPL grand final win|url=http://www.heraldsun.com.au/leader/south-east/sport/goalkeeper-ryan-scott-claims-jimmy-rooney-medal-in-bentleigh-greens-npl-grand-final-win/news-story/a63d211a9a93cae04673edda929252d4|website=Herald Sun|accessdate=11 September 2017}}</ref> Goalkeeper Ryan Scott took out the Jim Rooney Medal, awarded to the best player on the pitch.<ref name=\"2017 NPL Championship\" />\n\nBentleigh became the 6th member federation side in [[FFA Cup]] history to knock out an [[A-League]] opponent when it beat [[Wellington Phoenix FC]] 1-0 at Kingston Heath in August 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-au/news/ffa-cup-wellington-phoenix-fall-to-npl-side-bentleigh-greens/1qt9li75fgf6j1xplthnrtj6rn|title=FFA Cup Wrap: Wellington Phoenix upset by NPL side Bentleigh Greens, Luke Brattan suffers serious injury {{!}} Goal.com|access-date=2018-08-08|language=en}}</ref> Bentleigh beat [[Broadmeadow Magic FC|Broadmeadow Magic]] 4-0 at [[Wanderers Oval|Magic Park]] in the Round of 16<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/broadmeadow-magic-fc-v-bentleigh-greens-sc-ffa-cup-21-08-2018/1015426|title=Broadmeadow Magic FC vs Bentleigh Greens SC, FFA Cup, Round of 16, 21st Aug 2018|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref> and Heidelberg 1-0 in the quarter finals<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/bentleigh-greens-sc-v-heidelberg-united-fc-ffa-cup-26-09-2018/1020873|title=Bentleigh Greens SC vs Heidelberg United FC, FFA Cup, Quarter Finals, 26th Sep 2018|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref> to set up another clash with A League opposition, this time [[Adelaide United FC|Adelaide United.]] A goal in either half saw the Reds come away from Melbourne with a 2-0 win.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theffacup.com.au/match/bentleigh-greens-sc-v-adelaide-united-ffa-cup-05-10-2018/1028339|title=Bentleigh Greens SC vs Adelaide United, FFA Cup, Semi-Finals, 5th Oct 2018|website=FFA Cup|language=en|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref> In the league, the Greens finished a point off top spot, but lost 4-3 to [[Avondale FC|Avondale]] in the semi-final.  \n\nIn January 2019, new A-League team [[Western United FC]] announced that Bentleigh head coach [[John Anastasiadis]] would join the club as an assistant coach.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/highly-rated-anastasiadis-lands-a-league-coaching-role-with-western-melbourne|title=Highly-rated Anastasiadis lands A-League coaching role with Western Melbourne|website=The World Game|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> Anastasiadis' last game in charge was an NPL Victoria Round 13 victory over the previously undefeated Avondale, propelling the Greens to second spot on the table.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://websites.sportstg.com/round_info.cgi?a=MATCH&fixture=70083787&c=1-10178-0-513758-0&pool=1|title=FFV - NPL Match Centre|website=SportsTG|language=en|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref> John Gabrielson was appointed as the new head coach after Anastasiadis' departure. Gabrielson's tenure proved to be short-lived, with Frank McGrellis taking over in July 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://neoskosmos.com/en/142630/mcgrellis-answers-call-from-greens-to-coach-for-remainder-of-season/|title=Frank McGrellis answers call from Bentleigh Greens to coach remainder of season {{!}} Neos Kosmos|last=Stogiannou|first=George|date=2019-08-01|website=English Edition|language=en|access-date=2019-08-21}}</ref> After [[Kingston City FC|Kingston City]]'s relegation from the NPL Victoria was confirmed, Kingston's coach Nick Tolios was confirmed as the new Bentleigh Greens coach, mid-way through the 2019 NPL Victoria finals series. Tolios led the Greens to a 2-1 victory over premiers Heidelberg and a penalty shoot-out win over Avondale in the NPL Victoria Grand Final at [[AAMI Park]] to make it three championships in five years for the Cheltenham-based club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dailyfootballshow.com/greens-make-it-three-championships-in-five-years-with-shootout-win-over-avondale/,%20https://dailyfootballshow.com/?amp=1|title=Greens make it three championships in five years with shootout win over Avondale. {{!}} Daily Football Show|last=Lynch|first=Joey|language=en-AU|access-date=2019-09-16}}</ref>\n\n==Current squad==\n{{Fs start}}\n{{Fs player|no= 1|nat=AUS|name=Ryan Scott|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no= 4|nat=AUS|name=Charlie Fry|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 5|nat=AUS|name=Jack Webster|pos=DF}} ''([[captain (association football)|captain]])'' \n{{Fs player|no= 6|nat=AUS|name=Troy Ruthven|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 7|nat=AUS|name=[[Kieran Dover]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 8|nat=AUS|name=[[Andy Brennan]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no= 9|nat=AUS|name=[[Ben Litfin]]|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no= 10|nat=AUS|name=Tyson Holmes|pos=MF}} ''([[vice-captain|third captain]])''\n{{Fs player|no= 11|nat=AUS|name=George Kalas|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 14|nat=AUS|name=Marco Jankovi\u0107|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 15|nat=AUS|name=[[Ross Archibald]]|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs mid}}\n{{Fs player|no= 17|nat=AUS|name=Dimitri Hatzimouratis|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no= 18|nat=AUS|name=Matt Thurtell|pos=FW}}\n{{Fs player|no= 19|nat=AUS|name=Nick Glavan|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 20|nat=AUS|name=Jordan Grifkins|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs player|no= 23|nat=AUS|name=Trent Clulow|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 25|nat=AUS|name=Keanu Moore|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 26|nat=AUS|name=[[Lambros Honos|Ross Honos]]|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 30|nat=AUS|name=Joe O'Connor|pos=DF}}\n{{Fs player|no= 42|nat=AUS|name=Damion Wilson|pos=MF}}\n{{Fs player|no= |nat=AUS|name=Tom Baynard-Smith|pos=GK}}\n{{Fs end}}\n\n==Honours==\n*'''[[National Premier Leagues Victoria]]''' Champions 2015, 2017, 2019\n*'''[[National Premier Leagues Victoria]]''' Premiers 2016\n*'''[[Victorian Premier League]]''' Finalists 1996, 1997, 2001, 2002, 2019\n*'''[[Victorian State League Division 1]]''' Champions 1995\n*'''[[Victorian State League Division 2]]''' Runners Up 1993\n*'''[[Victorian State League Division 3]]''' Runners Up 1990\n*'''[[Victorian State League Division 4]]''' Runners Up 1989\n*'''[[Dockerty Cup]]''' Champions 2016, 2018\n*'''[[Dockerty Cup]]''' Runners Up 2017\n\n*'''[[FFV Community Shield]]''' Champions 2016, 2017, 2019\n*'''Hellenic Cup''' Champions 1991, 1996, 1997, 2002, 2003\n\n==Individual honours==\n*'''Victorian Premier League Player of the Year Award'''\n1996