0) (Menier Chocolate Factory, London, UK)&nbsp;\u2013 Eunuch\n*''Compulsion'' (by [[Rinne Groff]]) (2011) (Yale Repertory Theatre, Berkeley Repertory Theatre, and [[The Public Theater]])&nbsp;\u2013 Sid Silver<ref>Brantley, Ben.[http://theater.nytimes.com/2011/02/18/theater/reviews/18compulsion.html \"The Young Girl Pulls the Strings in This Relationship\"] ''The New York Times'', February 17, 2011</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n* ''[[Evita (musical)|Evita]]'' (cast album, 1979)\n* ''[[Sunday in the Park with George]]'' (cast album, 1984)<ref name=MPnet />\n* ''[[South Pacific (musical)|South Pacific]] (London Studio Cast)'' (1986)\n* ''Mandy Patinkin'' (1989)\n* ''Dress Casual'' (1990)\n* ''[[The Secret Garden (musical)|The Secret Garden]]'' (cast album, 1991)\n* ''Experiment'' (1994)\n* ''Oscar & Steve'' (1995)<ref name=MPnet />\n* ''[[Man of La Mancha]] (with Pl\u00e1cido Domingo)'' (1996)\n* ''Mamaloshen'' (1998)\n* ''[[Myths and Hymns]]'' (cast album, 1999)<ref>Suskin, Steven. [https://archive.is/20120906162642/http://www.playbill.com/features/article/65865.html/pg3 \"On the Record: 'Little Me', 'Charlie Brown' and especially, Adam Guettel\"] playbill.com, March 21, 1999</ref>\n* ''[[The Wild Party (LaChiusa musical)|The Wild Party]]'' (cast album, 2000)\n* ''Kidults'' (2001)\n* ''[[Mandy Patinkin Sings Sondheim]]'' (2002)\n* ''Diary: January 27, 2018'' (2018)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/mandy-patinkin-diary-january-27-2018-thomas-bartlett-out-now-nonesuch-2018-04-27|title=Mandy Patinkin's \"Diary: January 27, 2018,\" Recorded with Thomas Bartlett, Out Now on Nonesuch - Nonesuch Records|website=Nonesuch Records Official Website|language=en|access-date=2018-05-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180504212209/http://www.nonesuch.com/journal/mandy-patinkin-diary-january-27-2018-thomas-bartlett-out-now-nonesuch-2018-04-27|archive-date=May 4, 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* ''Diary: April/May 2018'' (2018)\n* ''Diary: December 2018'' (2019)\n* ''[[Children and Art (album)|Children and Art]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{commons}}\n* {{official website|http://www.mandypatinkin.org}}\n* {{IMDb name|0001597}}\n* {{IBDB name|55659}}\n* {{iobdb name|12577}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Mandy Patinkin\n| list =\n{{EmmyAward DramaLeadActor}}\n{{TonyAward MusicalFeaturedActor}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Patinkin, Mandy}}\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American people of Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male musical theatre actors]]\n[[Category:American male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Jewish American male actors]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:21st-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Nonesuch Records artists]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish American musicians]]\n[[Category:Juilliard School alumni]]\n[[Category:Organ transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:Outstanding Performance by a Lead Actor in a Drama Series Primetime Emmy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Tony Award winners]]\n[[Category:University of Kansas alumni]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Chicago]]\n[[Category:Cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:American male Shakespearean actors]]\n[[Category:Buddhists of Jewish descent]]\n", "name_user": "John B123", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mandy_Patinkin"}
{"title_page": "Cooper Rawson", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name=Sir Cooper Rawson\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image= Cooper Rawson.jpg\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Brighton (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton]]<br /> {{small|with [[George Tryon, 1st Baron Tryon|George Tryon]] (1922-1940)<br />[[John Erskine, Lord Erskine|Lord Erskine]] (1940-1941)<br />[[Anthony Marlowe]] (1941-1944)}}\n| term_start1= 1922\n| term_end1= 1944\n| predecessor1=[[Sir Charles Thomas-Stanford]]\n| successor1= [[Sir William Teeling]]\n| majority1=\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1876|7|26|}}\n| birth_place = [[Whetstone, Leicestershire]], [[England]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1946|01|11|1876|07|26}}\n| death_place = [[Hove]], [[Sussex]], England\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Elizabeth Rawson\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website =\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Sir Alfred Cooper Rawson''' (26 July 1876 \u2013 11 January 1946)<ref>{{Rayment-hc|b|5|date=March 2012}}</ref> was a British businessman and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician. After a decade in local government, he sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] from 1922 to 1944.\n\n== Business career ==\nBorn in Leicester, Rawson established himself in the [[road stone]] industry, becoming chairman of several companies, including the Montsorrel Granite Company, the Endaby Stoney Stanton Granite Company, John Ellis and sons, and [[Durex]] Ltd. He was a delegate to the International Road Congress in 1923 and in 1926, and in 1930 he was president of the Granite Guild; the following year he was president of the Institute of Quarrying.<ref name=\"times-obit\">{{cite news\n|title=Sir Cooper Rawson\n|date=12 January 1946\n|work=[[The Times]]\n|page=6\n|location=London\n}}</ref>\n\n== Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve ==\nDuring [[World War I]], he joined the [[Royal Naval Division]] as a [[sub-lieutenant]], transferring in 1916 to the [[Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve]] (RNVR). He served the rest of the war with the RNVR at [[The Crystal Palace]], becoming a temporary [[lieutenant commander]].<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\nRawson remained involved with the RNVR after the war, and in 1925 was made an honorary commander, attached to the RNVR's Sussex Division; in 1940 he was made an honorary [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] of the RNVR.<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\n== Politics ==\nRawson political career began in 1911, when he was elected to [[Metropolitan Borough of Wandsworth|Wandsworth Council]]. He was a Wandsworth councillor for 11 years, serving as mayor in 1918 to 1919, and was elected to the [[London County Council]] (LCC) in 1913.<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\nHe was elected [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Brighton (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton]] at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]],<ref>{{London Gazette\n |issue= 32775\n |date=8 December 1922\n |page=8703\n |city=London\n }}</ref> replacing the Conservative MP [[Charles Thomas-Stanford]],<ref name=\"craig1918-1949\">{{cite book\n |last=Craig\n |first=F. W. S.\n |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig\n |title=British parliamentary election results 1918\u20131949\n |origyear=1969\n |edition=3rd\n |year=1983\n |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn= 0-900178-06-X\n |page=103\n}}</ref> who had retired. He stood down from local government on his election to [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]]<ref name=\"times-obit\" /> and held his seat in the Commons at the next five general elections. Rawson [[United Kingdom general election records|holds the record]] for the largest number of votes ever polled by a candidate at a British general election, a record he achieved in the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 election]] by polling 75,205 votes. Such a feat also makes Rawson the record holder for the largest majority for an MP, at 62,253. This record was typical of a wider contest which saw an overwhelming Conservative victory.\n\nRawson told his local Conservative Association in October 1943 that he wanted to be relieved of his Parliamentary duties as soon as possible,<ref name=\"times-1943-10-25\">{{cite news\n|title=Brighton M.P. To Retire\n|date=25 October 1943\n|work=The Times\n|page=2\n|location=London\n}}</ref> and retired from [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] on 17 January 1944, by [[resignation from the British House of Commons|resigning his seat]] through the procedural device of accepting appointment as [[Steward of the Manor of Northstead]].<ref name=\"hoc-resignations\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04731.pdf \n |title=Appointments to the Chiltern Hundreds and Manor of Northstead Stewardships since 1850 \n |author=Department of Information Services \n |publisher=[[House of Commons Library]] \n |date=14 January 2010 \n |accessdate=13 August 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206041753/http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04731.pdf \n |archivedate=6 February 2011 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\nRawson was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[1926 New Year Honours]] List,<ref name=\"times-1926-honours\">{{cite news\n|title=New Year Honours. Four Peerages., Tribute To Church Army.\n|date=1 January 1926\n|work=The Times\n|page=12\n|location=London\n}}</ref> and in 1927 he was awarded the [[Legion of Honour]] by the government of France, for his work with the [[British League of Help]].<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\nIn July 1929, he was presented with a silver [[dinner bell]] by the National Federation of Granite and Roadstone Quarry Owners, in recognition of his services to the industry, and in particular of his efforts in blocking a Bill in Parliament which would have led to the expansion of council-owned quarries.<ref name=\"times-1929-07-20\">{{cite news\n|title=British Roadstone. Sir C. Rawson's Services To The Industry\n|date=20 July 1929\n|work=The Times\n|page=7\n|location=London\n}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nRawson married Elizabeth Robson in 1902. He died on 11 January 1946 at [[Hove, Sussex]], aged 69.<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-cooper-rawson | Cooper Rawson }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Brighton (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton]]\n | with   = [[George Tryon, 1st Baron Tryon|George Tryon]] 1922\u20131940\n | with2  = [[John Erskine, Lord Erskine|Lord Erskine]] 1940\u20131941\n | with3  = [[Anthony Marlowe]] 1941\u20131944\n | years  = [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]] \u2013 [[1944 Brighton by-election|1944]]\n | before = [[George Tryon, 1st Baron Tryon|George Tryon]]<br />[[Charles Thomas-Stanford]]\n | after  = [[Anthony Marlowe]]<br />[[William Teeling]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rawson, Alfred Cooper}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:Members of Wandsworth Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in construction]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy officers of World War I]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name=Sir Cooper Rawson\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image= Cooper Rawson.jpg\n| office1 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br> for [[Brighton (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton]]<br /> {{small|with [[George Tryon, 1st Baron Tryon|George Tryon]] (1922-1940)<br />[[John Erskine, Lord Erskine|Lord Erskine]] (1940-1941)<br />[[Anthony Marlowe]] (1941-1944)}}\n| term_start1= 1922\n| term_end1= 1944\n| predecessor1=[[Sir Charles Thomas-Stanford]]\n| successor1= [[Sir William Teeling]]\n| majority1=\n| birth_date = {{Birth date|df=yes|1876|7|26|}}\n| birth_place = [[Whetstone, Leicestershire]], [[England]]\n| death_date = {{Death date and age|df=yes|1946|01|11|1876|07|26}}\n| death_place = [[Hove]], [[Sussex]], England\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Elizabeth Rawson\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = \n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = \n| signature = \n| website =\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Sir Alfred Cooper Rawson''' (26 July 1876 \u2013 11 January 1946)<ref>{{Rayment-hc|b|5|date=March 2012}}</ref> was a British businessman and [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] politician. After a decade in local government, he sat in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] from 1922 to 1944.\n\n== Business career ==\nBorn in Leicester, Rawson established himself in the [[road stone]] industry, becoming chairman of several companies, including the Montsorrel Granite Company, the Endaby Stoney Stanton Granite Company, John Ellis and sons, and [[Durex]] Ltd. He was a delegate to the International Road Congress in 1923 and in 1926, and in 1930 he was president of the Granite Guild; the following year he was president of the Institute of Quarrying.<ref name=\"times-obit\">{{cite news\n|title=Sir Cooper Rawson\n|date=12 January 1946\n|work=[[The Times]]\n|page=6\n|location=London\n}}</ref>\n\n== Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve ==\nDuring [[World War I]], he joined the [[Royal Naval Division]] as a [[sub-lieutenant]], transferring in 1916 to the [[Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve]] (RNVR). He served the rest of the war with the RNVR at [[The Crystal Palace]], becoming a temporary [[lieutenant commander]].<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\nRawson remained involved with the RNVR after the war, and in 1925 was made an honorary commander, attached to the RNVR's Sussex Division; in 1940 he was made an honorary [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] of the RNVR.<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\n== Politics ==\nRawson political career began in 1911, when he was elected to [[Metropolitan Borough of Wandsworth|Wandsworth Council]]. He was a Wandsworth councillor for 11 years, serving as mayor in 1918 to 1919, and was elected to the [[London County Council]] (LCC) in 1913.<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\nHe was elected [[Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Brighton (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton]] at the [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922 general election]],<ref>{{London Gazette\n |issue= 32775\n |date=8 December 1922\n |page=8703\n |city=London\n }}</ref> replacing the Conservative MP [[Charles Thomas-Stanford]],<ref name=\"craig1918-1949\">{{cite book\n |last=Craig\n |first=F. W. S.\n |authorlink= F. W. S. Craig\n |title=British parliamentary election results 1918\u20131949\n |origyear=1969\n |edition=3rd\n |year=1983\n |publisher= Parliamentary Research Services\n |location=Chichester\n |isbn= 0-900178-06-X\n |page=103\n}}</ref> who had retired. He stood down from local government on his election to [[Palace of Westminster|Westminster]]<ref name=\"times-obit\" /> and held his seat in the Commons at the next five general elections. Rawson [[United Kingdom general election records|holds the record]] for the largest number of votes ever polled by a candidate at a British general election, a record he achieved in the [[1931 United Kingdom general election|1931 election]] by polling 75,205 votes. Such a feat also makes Rawson the record holder for the largest majority for an MP, at 62,253. This record was typical of a wider contest which saw an overwhelming Tory victory.\n\nRawson told his local Conservative Association in October 1943 that he wanted to be relieved of his Parliamentary duties as soon as possible,<ref name=\"times-1943-10-25\">{{cite news\n|title=Brighton M.P. To Retire\n|date=25 October 1943\n|work=The Times\n|page=2\n|location=London\n}}</ref> and retired from [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] on 17 January 1944, by [[resignation from the British House of Commons|resigning his seat]] through the procedural device of accepting appointment as [[Steward of the Manor of Northstead]].<ref name=\"hoc-resignations\">{{cite web\n |url=http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04731.pdf \n |title=Appointments to the Chiltern Hundreds and Manor of Northstead Stewardships since 1850 \n |author=Department of Information Services \n |publisher=[[House of Commons Library]] \n |date=14 January 2010 \n |accessdate=13 August 2010 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110206041753/http://www.parliament.uk/documents/commons/lib/research/briefings/snpc-04731.pdf \n |archivedate=6 February 2011 \n |df=dmy \n}}</ref>\n\n== Honours ==\nRawson was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in the [[1926 New Year Honours]] List,<ref name=\"times-1926-honours\">{{cite news\n|title=New Year Honours. Four Peerages., Tribute To Church Army.\n|date=1 January 1926\n|work=The Times\n|page=12\n|location=London\n}}</ref> and in 1927 he was awarded the [[Legion of Honour]] by the government of France, for his work with the [[British League of Help]].<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\nIn July 1929, he was presented with a silver [[dinner bell]] by the National Federation of Granite and Roadstone Quarry Owners, in recognition of his services to the industry, and in particular of his efforts in blocking a Bill in Parliament which would have led to the expansion of council-owned quarries.<ref name=\"times-1929-07-20\">{{cite news\n|title=British Roadstone. Sir C. Rawson's Services To The Industry\n|date=20 July 1929\n|work=The Times\n|page=7\n|location=London\n}}</ref>\n\n== Family ==\nRawson married Elizabeth Robson in 1902. He died on 11 January 1946 at [[Hove, Sussex]], aged 69.<ref name=\"times-obit\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=33em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-cooper-rawson | Cooper Rawson }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{succession box\n | title  = [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Brighton (UK Parliament constituency)|Brighton]]\n | with   = [[George Tryon, 1st Baron Tryon|George Tryon]] 1922\u20131940\n | with2  = [[John Erskine, Lord Erskine|Lord Erskine]] 1940\u20131941\n | with3  = [[Anthony Marlowe]] 1941\u20131944\n | years  = [[1922 United Kingdom general election|1922]] \u2013 [[1944 Brighton by-election|1944]]\n | before = [[George Tryon, 1st Baron Tryon|George Tryon]]<br />[[Charles Thomas-Stanford]]\n | after  = [[Anthony Marlowe]]<br />[[William Teeling]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rawson, Alfred Cooper}}\n[[Category:1876 births]]\n[[Category:1946 deaths]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1922\u20131923]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1923\u20131924]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1924\u20131929]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1929\u20131931]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1931\u20131935]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1935\u20131945]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Councillors in the London Borough of Wandsworth]]\n[[Category:Members of Wandsworth Metropolitan Borough Council]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Greater London]]\n[[Category:British businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Royal Naval Volunteer Reserve personn